 Here's how you can do it using JavaScript:

```javascript
let obj = {a: 1, b: 2, c: 3, d: 4}; // assuming this is your dictionary

// convert the dictionary into an array of key-value pairs
let keys = Object.keys(obj);

// sort the array alphabetically by key
let sortedKeys = keys.sort();

// create a new dictionary with sorted keys
let sortedObj = {};
for (let i=0; i<sortedKeys.length; i++) {
    sortedObj[sortedKeys[i]] = obj[sortedKeys[i]];
}

console.log(sortedObj);
```

This will output: 

```javascript
{ a: 1, b: 2, c: 3, d: 4 }
```
Note that the original dictionary is not modified in this process. This code only sorts and outputs the keys of the dictionary. If you want to sort by value as well, you can use a different approach like using `Array.prototype.sort()` with a custom compare function.
